<P>
Photo, A piece of San Diego history is being torn down in the South Bay. 
Several pieces, in fact. The redwood bridge that spans the Otay River on Beyer 
Boulevard, built in 1938 as part of Highway 101 between Los Angeles and 
Tijuana, will be replaced with a concrete structure. Each of the timbers is 20 
feet long and of a quality of redwood not available today. Below, crews begin 
stacking the massive beams, while above and left, workers cut away the bolts 
holding them together. VINCE COMPAGNONE /Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
