<HEADLINE>
<P>
QUAYLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Elizabeth Watson's statement that "maybe Bush deserves congratulations for 
choosing Quayle in spite of how foolish a move it seemed about a year ago," in 
response to Vice President Dan Quayle's public assessment of "Star Wars," 
deserves comment (letter, Sept. 21). 
</P>
<P>
The job President Bush gave Quayle -- to pop President Reagan's "Star War" 
bubble -- could have just as easily been given to any vice president at hand, 
or to the secretary of state, for that matter. Quayle remains a disastrously 
ignorant next-in-command in case President Bush dies in office. 
</P>
<P>
Seeing how responsibly Bush behaves in his job as President, I hope that at the 
end of his first term he will quietly replace Quayle with a fully competent and 
knowledgeable person, especially in view of the added danger to Bush from the 
Colombian drug cartels. 
</P>
<P>
This country has always taken its luck for granted. We shouldn't have to wait 
to see what happens. 
</P>
<P>
HILDA E. WENNER 
</P>
<P>
Santa Barbara 
</P>
</TEXT>
