<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: CABLE NETWORK TO JOIN CBS IN TELEVISING WINTER OLYMPICS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Olympic Games will go on cable television for the first time under a 
$50-million deal worked out between CBS Inc. and Turner Broadcasting Systems 
Inc. that covers the 1992 and 1994 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
Turner Network Television will air about 50 hours of programming for each 
Olympics. CBS, which paid $243 million for the 1992 Games at Albertville, 
France, and $300 million for the 1994 Games at Lillehammer, Norway, will air 
about 120 hours of each Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
