<HEADLINE>
<P>
REINER ON GANGS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More double-talk and equivocation by Dist. Atty. Ira Reiner (Metro, Sept. 20). 
</P>
<P>
He starts out talking firm and strong, " . . . Prosecutors will stop routinely 
plea-bargaining with gang members." But the article ends with a wimp, " . . . 
R. Dan Murphy, Reiner's director of special operations, conceded that there 
still will be cases where there is no option but to plea-bargain." 
</P>
<P>
Typical Reiner nonsense. 
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, it is misleading for him to use the term "plea-bargain." A limit 
or "lid" on the length of the county jail or state prison sentence is the 
practical result of all these negotiated sentences. Thus, a more accurate term 
would be "sentence-bargaining." 
</P>
<P>
RICHARD P. WINSTON 
</P>
<P>
Santa Monica 
</P>
</TEXT>
