<HEADLINE>
<P>
2 SOUTHERN BANKS PLAN $4.7-BILLION MERGER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ATLANTA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Citizens &amp; Southern Corp. and Sovran Financial Corp. announced a 
$4.7-billion merger Tuesday that will create the nation's 14th-largest banking 
company. 
</P>
<P>
C&amp;S, based in Atlanta, and Sovran, based in Norfolk, Va., will have total 
assets of $47 billion and almost 1,000 offices in seven states from Maryland to 
Florida. Under a newly formed holding company called Avantor Financial Corp., 
the two banks plan to maintain dual headquarters and retain current management. 
</P>
<P>
The merger comes five months after C&amp;S fought off a takeover bid by North 
Carolina's NCNB Corp. Unlike that proposal, the C&amp;S-Sovran deal is a 
friendly merger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
