<HEADLINE>
<P>
INTENSIVE CARE; 
</P>
<P>
UNITED WESTERN MEDICAL CENTERS ON MEND AFTER DOSE OF COST-CUTTING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE BERKMAN, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A United Western Medical Centers vice president was driving his BMW company car 
into the parking lot of the organization's Santa Ana corporate headquarters 
last December when he heard something that caused him to veer into a concrete 
bumper. 
</P>
<P>
He had been informed by one of the company's newly appointed administrators, 
who was sitting next to him, that the fleet of 15 fancy company cars assigned 
to hospital brass was about to be eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
"He said, 'That's a great idea.' But his actions betrayed his real feelings,' " 
recalled Charles S. Mack Jr., who had just become the hospital organization's 
chief operating officer when he advised the executive of the new cost-cutting 
policy. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Recruited by Directors 
</P>
<P>
Doing away with company cars was symbolic of many more far-ranging changes that 
Mack and his partner, Douglas L. Drumwright, have initiated at United Western 
since Dec. 6 when they took over the financially faltering operations of the 
nonprofit organization. 
</P>
<P>
Mack and Drumwright were recruited by United Western's board of directors to 
replace Wayne Schroeder, who resigned after serving as president of United 
Western for 21 years. 
</P>
<P>
United Western directors said in recent interviews that late last year they 
realized an immediate change in management was necessary to avert financial 
disaster. Schroeder, they said, was an "optimist" and a "visionary" who had 
been spending large sums of money on initiating new medical and advertising 
programs at a time when the organization instead desperately needed to 
retrench. 
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, who runs a consulting business out of his home in Santa Ana, refuses 
to directly address criticisms of his performance at United Western. He says 
only that he is proud of his record. "At the time I left," he contends, "the 
hospitals had a bright future." 
</P>
<P>
Not so, said company officials. For the fiscal year ended March 31, the 
hospital lost $30 million to $35 million and was on the brink of bankruptcy, 
they said. 
</P>
<P>
But the losses have slowed -- the company made a slight profit in July and 
August -- and company officials say it will be in the black by the end of the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
The heroes of the turnaround are Mack and Drumwright, United Western's chief 
executive officer. In just 10 months they have nursed United Western -- which 
runs a 327-bed hospital in Santa Ana and a 248-bed hospital and 241-bed 
skilled-nursing facility in Anaheim -- back to financial health. 
</P>
<P>
"Things were pretty dismal when they got there and the turnaround has been 
nothing short of phenomenal," said United Western director Thomas C. Hill. 
</P>
<P>
And partly on the strength of United Western's recovery, Mack and Drumwright 
recently got a contract to take over the administration of Care Enterprises 
Inc., a Tustin nursing home chain, as it struggles to reorganize and emerge 
from bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
Like hospitals nationwide, United Western's have had their profit margins 
squeezed by the cost-containment requirements of government and private medical 
insurers. Last year 53% of California hospitals lost money, according to the 
California Assn. of Hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
At United Western the financial bleeding was a massive hemorrhage. "In December 
and January bankruptcy was a real option and we told the employees that. We 
think honesty is the best policy," said Drumwright. 
</P>
<P>
During its last fiscal year, the organization suffered a huge loss. Drumwright 
said the company had an operating loss of $20 million and another $10 million 
from writedowns of hospital assets and of a bond refinancing for the Anaheim 
hospital. 
</P>
<P>
The financial deterioration did not happen overnight. Hill, who is an 
accountant and member of United Western's finance committee, said the 
organization would have posted a $4-million loss in fiscal 1988 had it not 
overestimated the amount of receipts the hospital would receive from Medi-Cal 
and Medicare. Instead, it posted net income of $600,000. 
</P>
<P>
Until they came to United Western, Drumwright and Mack had no experience in 
running a hospital. But they had other business experience that they thought 
would apply. In their resumes, Drumwright said he prepared a turnaround plan 
for Castle &amp; Cook, the giant Los Angeles-based international food company, 
and Mack cited his stint as chief financial officer of a health-care company 
during its transition from losing money to profitability. 
</P>
<P>
Drumwright, 44, and Mack, 38, recall with humor that their first joint business 
in 1983, a "doc-in-the-box" business in Northern California, was a flop. "It 
was our first start-up and liquidation in the first year," Mack said. 
</P>
<P>
But through it all, they contend, they have learned a lot about managing 
troubled companies. A year ago they teamed up and formed Alpha Partners to work 
with start-up and failing businesses. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
New Financial Officer 
</P>
<P>
Drumwright and Mack took the helm of United Western and abruptly changed its 
course, the company's directors said. They hired a new chief financial officer 
and restructured the organization's finance department. 
</P>
<P>
Also, they changed management at all three facilities. And throughout the 
organization they laid off about 300 people -- mostly management, professional 
and clerical staff -- got agreements to delay payments to vendors, dropped a 
money-losing Medi-Cal contract and generally quashed the previous management's 
exuberant spending. 
</P>
<P>
A monument to the spendthrift tendency of the former management, hospital 
officials say, are the elaborate corporate offices, redecorated at great 
expense several years ago in a modern gray and mauve motif. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Joseph Woo, chief of staff at Western Medical Center in Santa Ana, credited 
Schroeder, whom he described as "a charismatic dynamo," for greatly improving 
the stature of United Western over the years. He praised Schroeder for helping 
to establish the Santa Ana hospital's trauma and renal transplant programs. 
"These are the things that put Western Medical on the map in Orange County," 
Woo said. 
</P>
<P>
But he said that in the last year Schroeder had launched numerous costly new 
projects, frequently with little support from the medical staff. These 
programs, including plans for a 24-hour cancer center and high-tech "gamma 
knife" radiation therapy to treat brain tumors, were intended to boost United 
Western's image and future revenues. 
</P>
<P>
"We were just spending too much money too fast," said United Western Chairman 
Marven Howard. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Bankers 'Horrified' 
</P>
<P>
Drumwright said banks that lend money to United Western were surprised by the 
size of projected losses and "horrified" when the new management team talked 
about scrapping some projects that Schroeder had touted. "Wayne was pumping 
sunshine and his projections to the banks reflected that optimism," Drumwright 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The past management, Drumwright said, too often had fallen short in execution 
of its proposals. For instance, he said, United Western had bought and 
distributed 100 personal computers to staff doctors with the idea of forming a 
computerized information exchange between the doctors' offices and the 
hospitals. But the hospital linkup was never developed. The new management team 
also closed an outpatient diagnostic imaging and surgical center that United 
Western had opened in Irvine -- which Drumwright said was losing $1 million a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
And the very first day Drumwright and Mack took over, they said, they 
eliminated a controversial newspaper advertising campaign costing $50,000 a 
month that featured testimonials from the hospital's medical staff. 
</P>
<P>
"Employees did not like those ads and were not unhappy to see them gone," said 
Sandy Crawford, the Santa Ana hospital's director of nursing. 
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to cut costs, the new management team canceled contracts with 
outside companies for services such as accounting, computers, pharmacy and 
engineering, and began performing the services in house. 
</P>
<P>
While some new medical programs have been introduced at United Western 
hospitals in the last 10 months, they are being kept to a minimum, Howard said. 
Instead of installing expensive technology to attract patients, the new 
management says it is trying to stress the basics of good service. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Patient Pavilion' Plan 
</P>
<P>
There are plans, for example, to create a "patient pavilion" on the first floor 
of the Santa Ana hospital where all outpatient services will be grouped for 
greater convenience. 
</P>
<P>
Contrary to widespread speculation in the Orange County medical community, the 
new management and directors of United Western insist that they have no plans 
to sell any facility or close the Santa Ana hospital's trauma center as part of 
their cost-cutting drive. 
</P>
<P>
Those who operate United Western admit there still are problems. 
</P>
<P>
The Anaheim hospital first edged into profitability only in August, in response 
to stringent new cost controls. And Western Medical Center/Bartlett, the 
skilled nursing facility in Santa Ana, continues to lose money. 
</P>
<P>
Also, United Western officials acknowledged that this year the patient census 
at the flagship Santa Ana hospital has slipped, a condition they blame partly 
on the loss of Medi-Cal patients and partly on a countywide decline in hospital 
business reflecting a trend toward more outpatient care. 
</P>
<P>
So far this fiscal year, Drumwright said, United Western is $500,000 to $1 
million in the red. 
</P>
<P>
But there are clear signs of improvement. United Western officials say the 
Santa Ana hospital has returned to profitability and in July and August -- 
traditionally slow business months for hospitals -- and United Western as a 
whole has made a slight profit. 
</P>
<P>
And United Western officials are confident that by staying the current course 
the company will make a profit of $1 million to $2 million by the end of the 
current fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
"We will concentrate more on nuts and bolts," director Hill said. "We are going 
to mind the store." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Charles Mack Jr., left, and Douglas Drumwright cut costs to stop firm's 
financial hemorrhaging. ; Photo, Opulence of executive offices at Western 
Medical Center in Santa Ana reflects lavish spending of prior hospital 
administratrion. GLENN KOENIG / Los Angeles Times; Photo, Wayne Schroeder, 
United Western Medical Centers administrator for 21 years 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
